english:
  title: The Record of the Jeong Clan
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Jeong clan of Seowon is a great house of old standing. In their genealogy appears a certain Byeoljiang named Geuk-gyeong, who fathered Hyomun, the posthumously honored Jung-nangjiang. Hyomun fathered Yi, who became Daejangggun of the Sinhowwei with the rank of JoyuildaebU. Yi was originally named Chunyu. The Daejangggun married the daughter of Baek Ri-sin, a san-won of the Geumowwei, and fathered Hyeon, who became Gamchal-eosa and posthumously Sangseo-u Bokya. Hyeon married the daughter of Han Hui of Pyeongju, a Surung-jik official, and fathered Hae, who became Docheomuiji Chansong-sa with the posthumous name Janggyeong-gong. Janggyeong-gong married the daughter of Gim Gu, Pyeong-yeong, and fathered Cheong-ha-gun named Chaek, and also Pyeon Jeon-gyo-sa named I. With his second wife, the daughter of Hong Gu of the Joong-chan Chi-sa rank, who bore the posthumous name Gwangjeong, he had two daughters who married the Daeeeon Gyeongsa-man and the Jongbu-ryeong Choe Gwang respectively.

    Cheong-ha-gun married the daughter of Gim Sun, Pansamsasa of Sangnag-gun, the external granddaughter of Heo Moon-gyeong-gong of Yangcheon, Docheomuiji Joong-chan, and fathered Seol-heon Seongsaeng O and Seol-gok Seongsaeng Po. The Jeon-gyo official married and had a daughter who wed Gwak Chim, a Pansa.

    The Gyeong clan produced the current Sijnng-gong Bok-heung; the Choe clan produced Pjan Gaesong Maeng-son. Seol-heon married and fathered Gwak Chim, who held the rank of Jung-yun. His brother Seon-jin is now the great master of the Two Streets, abbot of Yeonbok Temple of the Jogye Order. The youngest, Un, passed the Jeong-yu examination and is now Pjan Jeon-gyo. His daughters married respectively to Manho Soonheung-gun Wang Seung, Samsau-yun Gwon Ju, and the retired Gyujeong Yu Jung-hyeon.

    Seol-gok married the daughter of Choe Moon-do Seongsaeng, Chaemuiji Challi of Chun-heon, and fathered Gan, who served as An-neung-ryeong but died young. His brother Yeon, renamed Chu with the courtesy name Gong-gwon, now goes by his courtesy name. He serves as Chaemseo Milzik-sa-sa and has retired to his home. His daughters married respectively to Jeongdang Moon-hak Won Song-su, Jeongdang Moon-hak Jeong Sa-do, and Hogoon Yi In-bu. The Yuan clan daughter's eldest daughter married Samsa-jwayun Heo Geum; the second married the Gyujeong Gim Yak-chae.

    The Jeong clan son Hong passed the Jeong-sa examination and serves as Ye-uyi Jeong-nang. The Yi clan has three sons: Bak-sil, a Lang-jang; Gang-sil, who passed the Jeong-sa examination as a scholar and became Sinhowwei Chammun; and Gyeon-sil, a Seung-sa. Chaemseo married the daughter of Ji-do Chaemuiji Han Dae-sun and fathered Chong, who placed first in the Byeong-jin examination and became Jwajung-eon. His younger brothers are Jeung and Tak. The daughter married Naebu-ryeong Yi Bin.

    The Jeong clan laid down fortune through generations. The Daejangggun's sacrifice for the realm is recorded in the registers of merit and listed in the ritual canon. Janggyeong-gong's great deeds became as a model to his house, and thus his descendants naturally abounded in worthy men.

    The Daejangggun, serving as an official of the Daeseong, was stationed at Seonggyeong Bunsae when a certain Choe Gwang-su of Seongju took advantage of the rebellion of Kim Si, heir of the Liao, and murdered Seonggyeong Byeongma-sa Choe Yeo-gong. He seized the city, appointed officials, gathered elite troops, and proclaimed the restoration of Goguryeo, sending inflammatory proclamations. This occurred in the fourth year of King Gojong, the year Jeong-chuk. Though the Daejangggun held a humble position, his anger blazed. Grasping his divine ax, he led Pil Hyeon-bo, Sin Juk, and more than ten others to strike Choe Gwang-su. With a single stroke of his ax, he cut him down and executed eighty of his followers, leaving the rest unmolested. Thus did disorder turn to peace. The king rejoiced greatly, and with exceptional honor promoted the Daejangggun to Jung-nangjiang, stationed him in the Nae-si-won, and granted him robes, a hat, saddle and horse, while rewarding his followers with distinctions of rank. After serving as Janggun and Si-nang, he was appointed Daejangggun. The year after the capital moved to Gangwha, Pil Hyeon-bo rebelled in Seonggyeong. The great ministers debated appeasement, and since Pil Hyeon-bo had once served under Yi, they sent Yi forth with the royal command. When he reached the Dae-dong River, his attendants begged him not to enter rashly. But Yi spoke boldly: "Having received the royal command, how dare I delay even a moment? Death is my duty." Upon meeting Pil Hyeon-bo, the latter rejoiced to have the Daejangggun and sought to make him his leader, alternately coaxing and threatening. Yet the Daejangggun never yielded, and thus met his end. The state honored him among the merit subjects of past ages.

    The Bokya, though not blessed by former virtue, fathered Janggyeong-gong, who from childhood burned with ambition for learning. In the shin-mi year of Wonjong, at eighteen he passed the Sa-ma examination, and the following year the state examination. The year after, he entered the Bi-seo-seong, soon transferring to Tongmun-won Nok-sa and Dae-gwan Seung, gradually advancing to the Moon-han-seo and Sagwan. In shin-sa he rose to U-jeong-eon Jiji-go, at the age of twenty-eight. That year he accompanied Chung-ryeol Wang to Happo in the campaign against Japan. In gye-mi he moved to Jwabo-gan; in winter to Gungi Soyun. In eul-yu he became Gunbu Jeong-nang; in byeong-sul, Bomunseo Dae-je. In jeong-hae, Soyun Bi-seo. In autumn of the seventh month, he accompanied the king northward and was promoted to Johuyn Daebu Gungi Yun; in winter, became Chong-nang of the Gunbu-sa with concurrent appointment as Deonmok Busa. In mu-ja, keeping his former post, he took the Spring Official Si-dok and soon was appointed Sa-gwan Susan-gwan. In winter, he became Jeoni Chong-nang Moon-han Si-dok Haksa. In gyeong-in, he was elevated to Milzik-sa, U-bu Seungji, U-sa-ui Daebu, and Sejahyu Yuseun. In im-jin, promoted to U-seungji, he presided over the examination of the Nam-seong and selected sixty-two scholars including Jeongdang Yi Eon-chung. In gap-o, he rose to Jisinja. In the autumn of the seventh month of won-jeong eul-mi, he became Bongeuk Daebu, Buji Milzik-sa-sa, and Panja Bi-seo-sa. He soon moved to Gughak Dae-sa-seong. In byeong-sin spring, he transferred to Pando Panja; in winter, became Dongji Milzik-sa-sa with concurrent duty as Sejawon-bin. In mu-sul autumn, he rose to Jisa Byeongjo Panja. In the eighth month, bearing the congratulatory message for the Sacred Festival, he was seen by the Seong-jong, who remarked upon his bearing. In gyeong-ja, as Milzik-sa, he became Jeoni Panja; that winter, Panja Samsasa. In shin-chuk, Jidoチャムオイ Sawsa. In gap-jin spring, Chamni Chaemuiji-sa. In eul-sa, promoted to Chansong-sa Yeon-yeong-jeon Dae-sa-hak Dongsu-sa. In the fourth month, he oversaw the examination for tribute scholars and selected thirty-three, among them Zhang Zia-bin—that year was praised for obtaining talent. The Jeongsung Han Jong-yu and Jeongsung Gim Young-don were both his disciples. In the sixth month, his old illness returned; in the evening he departed cleanly from the world. By his testament, his funeral was simple. He was fifty-two.

    Janggyeong-gong possessed fine bearing and a beard like painted silk. In repose his nature was magnanimous, yet when facing matters, he became clear-eyed and sharp, not to be moved—a man whose strength lay in his heart. Wang Wi-so and Song Bang-yeong, trusting in favor, misled Chung-ryeol Wang, planning to depose Chung-seon Wang and elevate the Seohung-hu Jeon, seeking approval from the Son of Heaven. Janggyeong-gong burned with indignation but could not yet speak. One day he encountered Song on the road. When provincial officials meet, courtesy dictates. But Song, proud, offered only a horseback bow. Janggyeong-gong feigned not to see, slowly dismounted, performed full courtesy, then spoke to Song's attendant: "This is your duty—why have you abandoned it?" He had his men seize Song's collar and strike his face. Song departed in shame. Is this not strength? From the time Janggyeong-gong entered service, he ever participated in selecting officials. All his recommendations met with universal approval. He once received a royal commission to become Lang-jung of the Jeong-dong-seong.

    Cheong-ha-gun possessed a forthright nature, unbound by restraint, and did not concern himself with household affairs. His wife's grandfather, the Chung-ryeol-gong, often praised him, saying: "Chaek is a true man." Through family merit, he gradually rose through offices, beginning as Nok-sa of the Seo Dae-bi Won, becoming Buk-myeon Dogam Panggwan, Heungwi-wwei Chammun-sa Byeoljiang. In the eighth year of Dae-dok, he was appointed Heungwi-wwei Boseung Hogoon with rank of Johuyn Daebu. The following autumn he moved to Pando Chong-nang; in winter, went out as Bu-Donggyeong Yusoo. In the twelfth month, Ye-bin Yun was added to his titles. In Dae-tok Jeong-mi, he was dispatched as Mok of Chungju, governing with strictness such that clerks dared not transgress. In Yeon-u Gi-mi, he returned as Chin-eo-gun Dae-hogoon, rising to Joong-hyeon Daebu.

    During the Jichi era, Chung-suk Wang suffered slander and remained in Beijing for five years. As the Shenyang Wang's power grew daily, scarcely one or two in a hundred officials maintained their integrity; most turned to curse the king and seek advantage. Cheong-ha-gun served then as Gunggul Dogam-sa. Hearing the royal treasury had emptied, he drew from old unnamed items of the Dogam budget, fashioned them into light tribute, and sent them to the Beijing residence. Chung-suk was deeply grateful. Upon his restoration, he at once appointed Cheong-ha-gun Eungyang-gun Sang-hogoon, elevated him to Tong-heon Daebu, and had him judge the Seon-gong bureau. Sickness came; he was enfeoffed as Cheong-ha-gun and allowed to live in quiet repose—thus was his clarity honored and his labor rewarded. He died at fifty-five.

    Seol-heon, whose courtesy name was Sa-gyeom, passed the examination in the Yeon-u jeong-sa year, rising to Chae-muiji Pyeong-ri with rank of Joong Dae-gwang. He received the title of Tujoong Jinuui Boori Gongsin and was given the posthumous name Moon-geuk. He received royal commission as Jegeyo Jeongdong Yugak, which the Chung-suk Wang had ordered transmitted to the Hyeon-neung; thus was he held in high regard by the Hyeon-neung.

    Seol-gok, whose courtesy name was Jung-bu, was eighteen in the byeong-in year of Tae-jeong. He successively passed the Jinsa examination and the Geup-je examination. He loved to study with Choe Jol-ong of Gyerim, learning his literary method, such that his poetry and prose bore no vulgar odor. He served as Bi-sun Wwei Chammun and Jeon-ui Jik-jang. In Jiwon Jeong-chuk, he entered the Ye-moon-gwan as a Sujan, bearing documents to Beijing. As Chung-suk Wang returned, he ascended to offer respects on the Shenyang Road. Chung-suk, seeing him once, loved him and kept him in attendance. In mu-in, his rank advanced suddenly; he became Jwasa-bo Jiji-gyo, Seong-gyun-gwan Sa-ye, and Ye-moon-gwan Eung-gyo Jiji-gyo, concurrent editor of the Chunchu-gwan. In gi-myo the first month, Chung-suk Wang passed away; in shin-sa, Chung-hye Wang ascended. He transferred to Jeoni Chong-nang. That summer, appointed Joong-hyeon Daebu, Jwasa-ui Daebu, Ye-moon-gwan Jik-je-hak Jiji-gyo. In autumn, his rank rose to Joong-jeong Daebu. As Sa-ui Daebu, the ancient rank of Gan-ui Daebu, he submitted many remonstrances, inciting the enmity of those in power. Not long after, he withdrew from office and remained at home. Someone slandered him to the court, saying: "The Jeong brothers may flee to the North, clustering about the Tae-jae." Thus came the order to exile both brothers: Moon-geuk to Nyeong-hae, Seol-gok to Ul-ju.

    Though in exile, Seol-gok remained serene, composing verses. Even now, reading his collected works, one perceives his verses warming the people with love and treating officials with severity—praised even to this day. In gap-sin, he journeyed to Beijing. The Seung-sang Byeol-go Seok-hwa Gong loved him greatly, intending to recommend him to the Son of Heaven, when unfortunately he fell ill. In eul-yu autumn, the fourteenth day of the seventh month, he passed in a traveler's inn. Chaemseo was but thirteen then; he bore the coffin homeward. My father Ga-jeong Gong wept for him, with verses saying "many cares sadden the heart." At that time they dwelt together in distant lands, never parting, so my father must have witnessed something to speak thus. His calligraphy was of the finest order. Upon our household screen, eight panels of his writing—carried off in shin-chuk winter. A pity. His widow, early widowed, taught her son with severity. Now near seventy, she grows ever stronger. Chaemseo in youth was often ill; growing older, he gradually learned the healing arts, able to expel harm and restore the vital force. Now nearing fifty, his spirit and radiance blossom. Perhaps Heaven, pitying Seol-gok's misfortune, has favored Chaemseo in compensation. Chaemseo and I passed the examination in the same year and both served as remonstrators; thus by righteousness I cannot refuse. I have arranged this record in brief and send it to the historians.
  footnotes:
    - Seowon refers to an ancient region in the Korean peninsula, associated with one of the great noble clans.
    - The Daejangggun's heroic defense against Choe Gwang-su's rebellion during the Mongol invasions is a celebrated moment in Korean history, demonstrating both martial prowess and unwavering loyalty.
    - The examination system mentioned throughout—Sa-ma, state examination, Jinsa—reflects the Goryeo period's adoption of Chinese-influenced civil service testing.
    - The biographical form follows the traditional Korean genealogical record (家傳), documenting not only official posts but personal character and moral conduct as measures of worth.
    - Seol-gok's exile to Ul-ju and his continued literary productivity despite hardship exemplify the Confucian ideal of the scholar-official maintaining integrity in adversity.
